## 3. Database & Models (Prisma-Level)

### 3.1 Existing Relevant Models (from `schema.prisma`)

- `User`:
  - Already has `email`, `emailVerified`, `passwordHash`, `dateOfBirth`, `country`, `status`, `metadata`, `preferences`, `lastLoginAt`.
  - `status` currently covers: `active | suspended | banned | deleted` (via `UserStatus`).
- `Account`, `Session`:
  - Already defined for NextAuth.
- `AuditLog`:
  - Generic audit trail for compliance and traceability.

### 3.2 Proposed New Auth-Specific Models

These are **aligned with** `02-ARCHITECTURE-REVIEW.mdc` section 8 and PM FR/NFR, but final schema changes must follow the DB task governance (no migrations are written in this document).

New logical tables (their exact Prisma shape will be implemented/migrated under the DB task as needed):

- `VerificationToken`
  - Fields: `id`, `userId`, `type` (`email_verify | password_reset`), `tokenHash`, `expiresAt`, `consumedAt`, `createdIp`, `createdUserAgent`, `createdAt`.
  - Indices:
    - `@@index([userId, type, expiresAt])`
    - `@@index([tokenHash])`
  - Purpose:
    - Single-use, time-bound tokens for email verification (FR-EMAIL-001/002) and password reset (FR-RESET-001/002).
    - Token stored **hashed** (\(NFR-SEC-001\)).

- `AgeVerification`
  - Fields: `id`, `userId`, `provider` (`veriff`), `providerSessionId`, `status` (`pending | passed | failed | needs_review`), `method`, `country`, `dobConfirmed`, `livenessScore?`, `fraudScore?`, `failureReason?`, `expiresAt?`, `metadata` (minimal JSON), `createdAt`, `updatedAt`, `verifiedAt?`.
  - Indices:
    - `@@index([userId])`
    - `@@index([providerSessionId])`
    - `@@index([status])`
  - Purpose:
    - Auditability (NFR-COMPL-001; PM §3.5, §3.6, Q5).
    - Minimal storage of provider data; raw docs/biometrics purged within 30 days (policy implemented at service layer + retention jobs, see §7.3).

### 3.3 User Account State

We will **not** introduce a new enum at DB level for auth-only states in this task; instead:

- Use `User.status` for coarse account states (`active`, `suspended`, `banned`, `deleted`).
- Use `User.metadata` JSON for finer-grained auth onboarding states, e.g.:
  - `authState.accountState` ∈ `["email_unverified", "age_pending", "age_denied", "active", "locked"]`.
  - `authState.lockReason`, `authState.lockUntil`.
- Reason:
  - Avoid destabilizing the broader domain schema at this stage.
  - Keeps auth states flexible while Architecture + Legal/Compliance may still evolve.
  - Still compatible with PM FR-AUTH-002 and architecture §3 (domain model & states).

Implementation detail (service-level):
- Provide strongly-typed TypeScript models to represent account state, with parsing/validation when reading/writing `User.metadata.authState`.

